org.mcnichol

Class BinaryFileReadWriter

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.mcnichol.BinaryFileReadWriter

  • public class BinaryFileReadWriter
extends java.lang.Object

    BinaryFileReadWriter

    This application writes fifty random integers to a file in binary format and then reads all values from same file and prints the max, min, mean, and sum statistics of the file.

    Description: This application leverages a static initializer block to configure formatting for the root Logger in addition to the default FileHandler and ConsoleHandler. It accepts a system property of logLevel which can be set to any of the logging levels defined in Level.

    It then initializes a statistics array leveraging initializeStatsArray() which populates the associated indexes with default starting values. An enum STATISTICS is used for meaningful indexing to ease readability and maintenance for the user.

    The generateRandomIntsAndWriteToFile() method is called where a FileOutputStream is created sourcing the DATA_FILE location with the append flag set to true. This is passed to a DataOutputStream which will be written to by an IntStream of 50 random integers populated by generateRandomIntStream().

    Note: During the write operation to the DataOutputStream an IOException can be thrown from within the IntStream. To handle this checked exception a FunctionalInterface IntConsumer is created and the IntStream is cast to this to ensure proper handling.

    The readIntegerFileAndPopulateStatistics() ()} method is called where an IntStream.builder() is created for storing all integers read from a binary file. A FileInputStream is created using the binary DATA_FILE which is passed into a DataInputStream. For each Integer read from this file, it runs a check on whether it is the max or min and summed using:

    • checkIfMaximumValueAndUpdateStatistics(int)
    • checkIfMinimumValueAndUpdateStatistics(int)
    • incrementSumAndUpdateStatistics(int)

    This file is read from until hitting an EOFException where it is caught and the mean is computed using computeMeanOfIntStreamAndUpdateStatistics(IntStream).

    Note: If an IOException occurs during the read process the exception is caught and the system will exit.

    At the completion of the program the statistics are formatted and printed to the active Handler by calling printStatistics()

    Usage: This application can be run from the terminal by navigating to the root directory and running the gradle wrapper on both *Nix and Windows systems. If you have issues ensure your JAVA_HOME environment variable is set and can be seen from your PATH.

    • ./gradlew run (*Nix)
    • gradlew.bat run (win)

    Note: Logging levels can be configured by setting the gradle property ./gradlew run -DlogLevel=FINE
